uments and sites, bygone eras and political regimes, even your genetic ancestry, can become wrapped up in polarized political debates. They also highlight how heritage, which is often thought of as a common good, can be dangerous in times of political polarization – erasing nuances between ‘us’ and ‘them’. Together, the texts pave the way for a better understanding of the political role of heritage in society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCultural propertyxPolitical aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPolitical aspects. 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspects. 0aNational characteristicsxPolitical aspects. 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aRight and left (Political science). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aHeritage Studies, Cultural Studies (General), Archaeology.1 aBernbeck, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCesari, Chiara de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColwell, Chip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález-Ruibal, Alfredo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHølleland, Herdis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Rebecca Futo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKällén, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiklasson, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiklasson, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThorleifsson, Cathrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books C